# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-elastic-beanstalk
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] Autoscaling differs from having a fixed daily, weekly, or yearly cycle of server use in that it is responsive to actual usage patterns, and thus reduces the potential downside of having too few or too many servers for the traffic load.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] For instance, if traffic is usually lower at midnight, then a static scaling solution might schedule some servers to sleep at night, but this might result in downtime on a night where people happen to use the Internet more (for instance, due to a viral news event).
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] Autoscaling, on the other hand, can handle unexpected traffic spikes better.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] In the list below, we use the terminology used by Amazon Web Services (AWS).
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] However, alternative names are noted and terminology that is specific to the names of Amazon services is not used for the names.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] Amazon Web Services launched the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) service in August 2006, that allowed developers to programmatically create and terminate instances (machines).
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] At the time of initial launch, AWS did not offer autoscaling, but the ability to programmatically create and terminate instances gave developers the flexibility to write their own code for autoscaling.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] Third-party autoscaling software for AWS began appearing around April 2008.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] These included tools by Scalr and RightScale.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] RightScale was used by Animoto, which was able to handle Facebook traffic by adopting autoscaling.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] On May 18, 2009, Amazon launched its own autoscaling feature along with Elastic Load Balancing, as part of Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] Autoscaling is now an integral component of Amazon's EC2 offering.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] Autoscaling on Amazon Web Services is done through a web browser or the command line tool.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] In May 2016 Autoscaling was also offered in AWS ECS Service.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] On-demand video provider Netflix documented their use of autoscaling with Amazon Web Services to meet their highly variable consumer needs.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] They found that aggressive scaling up and delayed and cautious scaling down served their goals of uptime and responsiveness best.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] In an article for *TechCrunch*, Zev Laderman, the co-founder and CEO of Newvem, a service that helps optimize AWS cloud infrastructure, recommended that startups use autoscaling in order to keep their Amazon Web Services costs low.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] Various best practice guides for AWS use suggest using its autoscaling feature even in cases where the load is not variable.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] Netflix's internal best practices require every instance to be in an autoscaling group, and its conformity monkey terminates any instance not in an autoscaling group in order to enforce this best practice.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] On June 27, 2013, Microsoft announced that it was adding autoscaling support to its Windows Azure cloud computing platform.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] Documentation for the feature is available on the Microsoft Developer Network.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] Oracle Cloud Platform allows server instances to automatically scale a cluster in or out by defining an auto-scaling rule.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] These rules are based on CPU and/or memory utilization and determine when to add or remove nodes.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] On November 17, 2014, the Google Compute Engine announced a public beta of its autoscaling feature for use in Google Cloud Platform applications.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] As of March 2015, the autoscaling tool is still in Beta.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] In a blog post in August 2014, a Facebook engineer disclosed that the company had started using autoscaling to bring down its energy costs.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] The blog post reported a 27% decline in energy use for low traffic hours (around midnight) and a 10-15% decline in energy use over the typical 24-hour cycle.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] Autoscaling by default uses *reactive* decision approach for dealing with traffic scaling: scaling only happens in response to real-time changes in metrics.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] In some cases, particularly when the changes occur very quickly, this reactive approach to scaling is insufficient.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] Two other kinds of autoscaling decision approaches are described below.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] This is an approach to autoscaling where changes are made to the minimum size, maximum size, or desired capacity of the autoscaling group at specific times of day.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] Scheduled scaling is useful, for instance, if there is a known traffic load increase or decrease at specific times of the day, but the change is too sudden for reactive approach based autoscaling to respond fast enough.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] AWS autoscaling groups support scheduled scaling.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] This approach to autoscaling uses predictive analytics.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] The idea is to combine recent usage trends with historical usage data as well as other kinds of data to predict usage in the future, and autoscale based on these predictions.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] For parts of their infrastructure and specific workloads, Netflix found that Scryer, their predictive analytics engine, gave better results than Amazon's reactive autoscaling approach.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/autoscaling] On November 20, 2018, AWS announced that predictive scaling would be available as part of its autoscaling offering.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment contrasts with *continuous delivery* (also abbreviated CD), a similar approach in which software functionalities are also frequently delivered and deemed to be potentially capable of being deployed, but are actually not deployed.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] As such, continuous deployment can be viewed as a more complete form of automation than continuous delivery.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment has been adopted by software companies such as Meta, Microsoft, Atlassian, IBM, Adobe, and Tesla.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment extends the principles of continuous integration and delivery by including fully automated production deployment without the need for manual approval, instead relying on rigorous automated testing.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] Reviews may still take place in the form developer-developer code reviews, but the need for intermediary reviewers such as a change-advisory board is minimized.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] Because code changes are deployed automatically, continuous deployment requires a much higher standard of automated testing, as test quality determines the reliability of releases.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] Without this, the risk of introducing production failures outweighs the benefits of deployment automation.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] In addition, continuous deployment emphasizes small incremental changes and dark launches through the use of feature toggles.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] Developers can deploy code into production months before a public release by gradually adding functionality in small chunks, verifying stability, and then enabling the feature for users when it is considered ready.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment removes the need to wait for releases, as once a change passes internal testing it is automatically deployed to production.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] This allows for shorter time-to-market and more frequent releases, which in turn increases customer satisfaction and provides companies with more marketing opportunities.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] A major motivation for continuous deployment is that deploying software into the field more often makes it easier to find, catch, and fix bugs.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] Deploying small, incremental changes makes it easier to trace the origin of bugs, since issues will be isolated to a recent and relatively small code change.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] Under this methodology, new software features can be released to customers more quickly and frequently after their development, accelerating the delivery of value to customers and enhancing customer satisfaction.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] Teams can begin to collect customer feedback almost immediately, driving rapid innovation of relevant features.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] Continuous delivery requires a significant investment in adequate test coverage, real-time monitoring, and strong continuous integration pipelines to prevent bugs from reaching production.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] Customers may also find software that is constantly changing creates a learning curve which can negatively affect their experience.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] Moving to continuous delivery is also a culture shift for developers who are accustomed to traditional release cycles, often requiring a proven DevOps process.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] Adopting this process requires collaboration among multiple stakeholders, including development teams, leadership, operations, and quality assurance.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/continuous-deployment] In an environment in which data-centric microservices provide the functionality, and where the microservices can have multiple instances, continuous deployment consists of instantiating the new version of a microservice and retiring the old version once it has drained all the requests in flight.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] The first public platform as a service was Zimki, launched by Fotango, a London-based company owned by Canon Europe.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] It was developed in 2005, had a beta launch in March 2006 and a public launch at EuroOSCON in 2006.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] At the time of its closure, Zimki had several thousand developer accounts.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] It had demonstrated the technical viability of Platform as a Service, but also provided the first example of the perils of being dependent on a single provider.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] The original intent of PaaS was to simplify the writing of code, with the infrastructure and operations handled by the PaaS provider.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] Originally, all PaaSes were in the public cloud.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] Because many companies did not want to have everything in the public cloud, private and hybrid PaaS options (managed by internal IT departments) were created.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] PaaS provides an environment for developers and companies to create, host and deploy applications, saving developers from the complexities of infrastructure (setting up, configuring and managing elements such as servers and databases).
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] PaaS can improve the speed of developing an app, and allow its user to focus on the application itself.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] With PaaS, the customer manages applications and data, while the provider (in public PaaS) or IT department (in private PaaS) manages runtime, middleware, operating system, virtualization, servers, storage and networking.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] Development tools provided by the vendor are customized according to the needs of the user.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] The user can choose to maintain the software, or have the vendor maintain it.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] Besides the service engineering aspects, PaaS offerings include mechanisms for service management, such as monitoring, workflow management, discovery and reservation.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] Disadvantages of various PaaS providers as cited by their users include increased pricing at larger scales, lack of operational features, reduced control, and the difficulties of traffic routing systems.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] There are several types of PaaS, including public, private and hybrid.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] PaaS was originally intended for applications on public cloud services, before expanding to include private and hybrid options.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] Public PaaS is derived from software as a service (SaaS), and is situated in cloud computing between SaaS and infrastructure as a service (IaaS).
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] SaaS is software hosted in the cloud so that it does not reside or run on customer computers.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] IaaS provides virtual hardware from a provider with adjustable scalability.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] In IaaS, the server is managed by the user, whereas in PaaS by the provider.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] A private PaaS can typically be downloaded and installed either in a company's on-premises data center, or in a public cloud.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] Once the software is installed on one or more machines, the private PaaS arranges the application and database components into a single hosting platform.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] Hybrid PaaS is typically a deployment consisting of a mix of public and private deployments.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] A communications platform as a service (CPaaS) is a cloud-based platform that enables developers to add real-time communications features (voice, video, and messaging) in their own applications without building back-end infrastructure and interfaces.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] Also, CPaaS and hardware and software specifications are specifically designed to support (tele)communications applications.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] These applications and their usage are much more sensitive to jitter, latency and packet losses.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] Hosted PBX, cellular networks, (near real-time) applications typically are deployed on CPaaS platforms.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] Initiated in 2012, mobile PaaS (mPaaS) provides development capabilities for mobile app designers and developers.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] The Yankee Group identified mPaaS as one of its themes for 2014.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] There are various types of PaaS providers.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] All offer application hosting and a deployment environment, along with various integrated services.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] Services offer varying levels of scalability and maintenance.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] Developers can write an application and upload it to a PaaS that supports their software language of choice, and the application runs on that PaaS.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] The UK Government encourages departments to make use of public cloud solutions as a first option.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] PaaS is in use within UK Government but the technology community within government notes that PaaS providers may restrict the software, languages and interfaces they are willing to support.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/platform-as-a-service] The Government operated its own GOV.UK PaaS service from 2015 until 2023, but this has now been decommissioned.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] A **web application** (or **web app**) is application software that is created with web technologies and runs via a web browser.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Web applications emerged during the late 1990s and allowed for the server to dynamically build a response to the request, in contrast to static web pages.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Web applications are commonly distributed via a web server.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] There are several different tier systems that web applications use to communicate between the web browsers, the client interface, and server data.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Each system has its own uses as they function in different ways.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] However, there are many security risks that developers must be aware of during development; proper measures to protect user data are vital.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Web applications are often constructed with the use of a web application framework.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Single-page applications (SPAs) and progressive web apps (PWAs) are two architectural approaches to creating web applications that provide a user experience similar to native apps, including features such as smooth navigation, offline support, and faster interactions.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Modern browsers such as Chrome offer sandboxing for every browser tab which improves security and restricts access to local resources.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] No software installation is required as the app runs within the browser which reduces the need for managing software installations.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] With the use of remote cloud services, customers do not need to manage servers as that can be left to the developer and the cloud service and can use the software with a relatively low power, low-resource PC such as a thin client.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] The source code of the application can stay the same across operating systems and devices of users with the use of responsive web design, since it only needs to be compatible with web browsers which adhere to web standards, making the code highly portable and saving on development time.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Numerous JavaScript frameworks and CSS frameworks facilitate development.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] The concept of a "web application" was first introduced in the Java language in the Servlet Specification version 2.2, which was released in 1999.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] At that time, both JavaScript and XML had already been developed, but the XMLHttpRequest object had only been recently introduced on Internet Explorer 5 as an ActiveX object.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Beginning around the early 2000s, applications such as "Myspace (2003), Gmail (2004), Digg (2004), [and] Google Maps (2005)," started to make their client sides more and more interactive.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] A web page script is able to contact the server for storing/retrieving data without downloading an entire web page.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] The practice became known as Ajax in 2005.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Eventually this was replaced by web APIs using JSON, accessed via JavaScript asynchronously on the client side.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] In earlier computing models like client-server, the processing load for the application was shared between code on the server and code installed on each client locally.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] In other words, an application had its own pre-compiled client program which served as its user interface and had to be separately installed on each user's personal computer.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] An upgrade to the server-side code of the application would typically also require an upgrade to the client-side code installed on each user workstation, adding to the support cost and decreasing productivity.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Additionally, both the client and server components of the application were bound tightly to a particular computer architecture and operating system, which made porting them to other systems prohibitively expensive for all but the largest applications.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Later, in 1995, Netscape introduced the client-side scripting language called JavaScript, which allowed programmers to add dynamic elements to the user interface that ran on the client side.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Essentially, instead of sending data to the server in order to generate an entire web page, the embedded scripts of the downloaded page can perform various tasks such as input validation or showing/hiding parts of the page.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Traditional PC applications are typically single-tiered, residing solely on the client machine.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] In contrast, web applications inherently facilitate a multi-tiered architecture.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Though many variations are possible, the most common structure is the three-tiered application.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] In its most common form, the three tiers are called *presentation*, *application* and *storage*.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] The first tier, presentation, refers to a web browser itself.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] The second tier refers to any engine using dynamic web content technology (such as ASP, CGI, ColdFusion, Dart, JSP/Java, Node.js, PHP, Python or Ruby on Rails).
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] The third tier refers to a database that stores data and determines the structure of a user interface.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Essentially, when using the three-tiered system, the web browser sends requests to the engine, which then services them by making queries and updates against the database and generates a user interface.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] The 3-tier solution may fall short when dealing with more complex applications, and may need to be replaced with the n-tiered approach; the greatest benefit of which is how business logic (which resides on the application tier) is broken down into a more fine-grained model.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Another benefit would be to add an integration tier, which separates the data tier and provides an easy-to-use interface to access the data.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] For example, the client data would be accessed by calling a "list_clients()" function instead of making an SQL query directly against the client table on the database.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] This allows the underlying database to be replaced without making any change to the other tiers.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] There are some who view a web application as a two-tier architecture.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] This can be a "smart" client that performs all the work and queries a "dumb" server, or a "dumb" client that relies on a "smart" server.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] The client would handle the presentation tier, the server would have the database (storage tier), and the business logic (application tier) would be on one of them or on both.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] While this increases the scalability of the applications and separates the display and the database, it still does not allow for true specialization of layers, so most applications will outgrow this model.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Security breaches on these kinds of applications are a major concern because it can involve both enterprise information and private customer data.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Protecting these assets is an important part of any web application, and there are some key operational areas that must be included in the development process.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] This includes processes for authentication, authorization, asset handling, input, and logging and auditing.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Building security into the applications from the beginning is sometimes more effective and less disruptive in the long run.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] Writing web applications is simplified with the use of web application frameworks.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] These frameworks facilitate rapid application development by allowing a development team to focus on the parts of their application which are unique to their goals without having to resolve common development issues such as user management.
[src:aws-elastic-beanstalk/web-application] In addition, there is potential for the development of applications on Internet operating systems, although currently there are not many viable platforms that fit this model.
